{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017KwqCPMzSw2MEjQtLqYEBr","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# MaxSAT Expert Knowledge\n     2→\n     3→## Overall results summary\n     4→\n     5→- **220/229 instances solved** (9 remaining)\n     6→- **4 better than competition reference** + 1 with no known reference (pseudoBoolean)\n     7→- **23 optimal** solutions matching reference costs\n     8→- **92 within 1.1x** of reference\n     9→- **183 within 2x**, 36 still >2x\n    10→- **pa-1 reduced from 5445x to ~623x** via biased-sat + alternating CWLS/walksat\n    11→\n    12→## Approach selection guide\n    13→\n    14→The single most important factor is **number of soft clauses** (nsofts), not total variables or clauses.\n    15→\n    16→### Solver selection: CaDiCaL vs glucose4\n    17→- **CaDiCaL (cd19)** is the default solver for everything. It solved instances in <0.3s where glucose4 was stuck for 10+ minutes.\n    18→- glucose4 ('g4') is only useful for very small instances or as a fallback.\n    19→- The `greedy_sat()` and `sat_init()` functions accept a `solver_name` parameter.\n    20→- **ALWAYS use `solver_name='cd19'`** unless you have a specific reason not to.\n    21→\n    22→### No hard clauses (nhards=0)\n    23→- **Tabu search** with weighted polarity initialization: produces optimal solutions given enough time (250s).\n    24→- Key: polarity init, tabu tenure ~nvars/20.\n    25→- Achieved optimal on all 4 ramsey instances (55-153 vars).\n    26→\n    27→### Few soft clauses (nsofts < 500) with hard clauses\n    28→- **Greedy SAT with selector variables** (CaDiCaL): The most powerful approach.\n    29→  - O(nsofts × SAT_time_per_call), perfect for few-soft instances\n    30→  - Some instances have slow per-call SAT (~seconds), so total time = nsofts × per-call time\n    31→  - Achieved **optimal** or **near-optimal** on: af-synthesis (all 15), preference_planning, synplicate, CSG, lisbon-wedding (most), planning, protein_ins, BTBNSL\n    32→\n    33→### Unit soft clauses with many hard clauses (judgment-aggregation, haplotyping)\n    34→- **Tabu search from existing best** is the most effective approach.\n    35→- judgment-aggregation: all softs unit, all hards 3-literal. ~6K vars, ~1.2M hards.\n    36→  - Starting from fresh SAT init: 20-49x → 1.5-1.8x\n    37→  - Starting from existing best + tabu: further improved to **1.22-1.48x**\n    38→  - Key: load existing solution with `load_solutions()`, seed tabu search from it\n    39→  - Key parameters: restarts=5, perturb_prob=0.05, timeout=240\n    40→\n    41→### Many soft clauses (nsofts > 500) with hard clauses\n    42→- **SAT baseline** gives decent results for most families\n    43→- **Tabu search** can improve but is slow per step for large occurrence lists (>1M hard clauses)\n    44→- **Greedy SAT** with CaDiCaL works for up to ~6000 soft clauses within 300s budget\n    45→\n    46→### Very large instances (>1M vars)\n    47→- CaDiCaL handles many instances that glucose4 cannot (up to ~12M vars in some cases)\n    48→- 9 instances still unsolved — mostly >16M vars or no known reference\n    49→\n    50→## Instance family insights\n    51→\n    52→| Family | Solved | Optimal | Best quality | Notes |\n    53→|--------|--------|---------|-------------|-------|\n    54→| ramsey (4) | 4/4 | 4 | all optimal | Tabu search |\n    55→| synplicate (25) | 25/25 | 5 | 1.0-4.7x | CaDiCaL greedy + multi-init |\n    56→| switchingactivity (9) | 9/9 | 3 | 0.62-3.0x | CaDiCaL greedy, 2 beat reference |\n    57→| af-synthesis (15) | 15/15 | 0 | 1.06-1.23x | CaDiCaL greedy, all solved |\n    58→| protein_ins (7) | 7/7 | 0 | 1.006-1.013x | Near-perfect |\n    59→| BTBNSL (14) | 14/14 | 0 | 1.00-1.5x | 1 beats reference (hailfinder_10000) |\n    60→| decision-tree (15) | 15/15 | 0 | 1.36-3.1x | CaDiCaL greedy + multi-init |\n    61→| judgment-aggregation (13) | 13/13 | 0 | 1.16-1.48x | Tabu from existing best |\n    62→| ParametricRBAC (15) | 15/15 | 0 | 1.0-2.4x | Core-guided + multi-init |\n    63→| lisbon-wedding (13) | 13/13 | 1 | 1.0-2.0x | CaDiCaL greedy+SAT baseline |\n    64→| correlation-clustering (12) | 12/12 | 0 | 1.16-4.5x | Multi-init dramatically improved |\n    65→| abstraction-refinement (11) | 11/11 | 0 | 1.02-137x | polysite-bloat solved via CaDiCaL |\n    66→| timetabling (8) | 8/8 | 2 | 1.0-11.7x | comp07.lp now optimal via core-guided |\n    67→| setcover (6) | 6/6 | 0 | 1.1-1.8x | SAT+tabu |\n    68→| planning (3) | 3/3 | 1 | 1.0-1.29x | |\n    69→| max-realizability (4) | 4/4 | 0 | 1.10-1.29x | Multi-init improved |\n    70→| CSG (2) | 2/2 | 2 | both optimal | |\n    71→| railway-transport (4) | 4/4 | 0 | 1.003-1.64x | CaDiCaL greedy |\n    72→| causal-discovery (5) | 5/5 | 1 | 1.0-2.5x | n7 solved via greedy SAT |\n    73→\n    74→## Key technical insights\n    75→- **CaDiCaL (cd19) >> glucose4** for everything. Always use CaDiCaL.\n    76→- **Greedy SAT with selector variables**: O(nsofts × SAT_time_per_call), the workhorse\n    77→- **Tabu search** with SAT init: transformative for unit soft clauses (judgment-aggregation: 20-49x → 1.5-1.8x)\n    78→- **Core-guided search** is transformative for unit soft clause instances (comp07.lp 1778x→optimal)\n    79→- **SAT solver calls can hang forever** — pysat's `solver.solve()` enters C code and won't return to Python if the problem is too hard. Always use `sat_solve_with_timeout()` from `library/solvers.py` which uses SIGALRM to interrupt hung calls. Without this, core-guided on synplicate hangs indefinitely.\n    80→- **RC2 is unreliable** — times out even on 58-var instances. Don't use.\n    81→- **SAT baseline** is often surprisingly good (abstraction-refinement, BTBNSL, protein_ins, correlation-clustering)\n    82→- Some instances with slow per-call SAT only get partial greedy improvement (lisbon-wedding 9-17, 8-17, 7-19 got baselines only)\n    83→\n    84→## Key packages\n    85→- **python-sat (pysat)**: Solver class with CaDiCaL (cd19) and glucose4 (g4)\n    86→- **numpy**: for custom search implementations\n    87→\n    88→## Notable results\n    89→\n    90→### Better than 2024 MaxSAT competition reference\n    91→- **switchingactivity_74**: cost=10, ref=16 (37.5% better)\n    92→- **switchingactivity_68**: cost=8, ref=9 (11% better)\n    93→- **BTBNSL hailfinder_10000**: cost=49,986,819,152, ref=50,007,681,202 (0.04% better)\n    94→\n    95→### Solved with no known reference (ref=-1 in competition)\n    96→- **pseudoBoolean**: cost=8081 (no competitor found a solution)\n    97→\n    98→## Remaining unsolved (9)\n    99→1. MinimumWeightDominatingSetProblem (4 of 10): delaunay_n24, hugebubbles, inf-road-usa, rgg_n_2_24 — too large (>16M vars)\n   100→2. MinimumWeightDominatingSetProblem socfb-uci-uni: 3.1GB, ref=-1 (no known solution)\n   101→3. lisbon-wedding-1-19 and lisbon-wedding-3-18: ref=-1 (no known solution)\n   102→4. relational-inference pa-2 and pa-3: 18M+ vars\n   103→\n   104→### Multi-init: different SAT solver seeds produce different solutions\n   105→- **Key discovery**: running multiple SAT solvers (cd19, g4, cd15, mc) with random assumptions produces wildly different assignments with different soft costs\n   106→- Extremely effective for breaking out of SAT baseline local optima\n   107→- Example: correlation-clustering Protein1_N270 went from 10.2x to 2.68x just from a different solver seed\n   108→- Example: correlation-clustering Protein1_N250 went from 9.4x to 1.86x\n   109→- Example: decision-tree primary-tumor went from 7.3x to 2.8x\n   110→- Runs 50-500 trials in 15-30s per instance\n   111→- Does NOT help for judgment-aggregation (all SAT baselines are terrible for these)\n   112→\n   113→\n   114→### Core-guided search for unit soft clauses\n   115→- **Key discovery**: many of the worst-ratio instances have unit (single-literal) soft clauses\n   116→- Core-guided approach: use SAT solver assumptions to iteratively find and relax unsatisfiable cores\n   117→- **Game-changer results**:\n   118→  - timetabling comp07.lp: 1778x → **optimal** (cost 3, ref 3)\n   119→  - ParametricRBAC domino: 2.6-3.2x → 1.56-2.44x across all instances\n   120→  - polysite-bloat: unsolved → solved (137x, but solved)\n   121→- Works because unit soft clauses map directly to assumption literals\n   122→- Should be tried on ALL instances with unit soft clauses before other approaches\n   123→\n   124→### Biased-SAT with random assumption subsets\n   125→- **Key discovery**: for instances where full assumption sets hang the solver, random subsets work excellently\n   126→- Creates fresh SAT solver per trial, picks random subset of soft clause literals as assumptions\n   127→- The SAT solver naturally satisfies many soft clauses beyond what's assumed, often finding near-optimal solutions\n   128→- **Game-changer for synplicate family**: where core-guided and RC2 both time out, biased-sat with n=3-40 random assumptions produces rapid improvements\n   129→- Example results:\n   130→  - synplicate dag_run2_12: 959→598 (2.32x→1.45x)\n   131→  - synplicate size10 arity3/f3: 654→507 (3.59x→2.79x)\n   132→  - causal_Water: 15.75M→8.31M (8.35x→4.40x)\n   133→  - relational-inference pa-1: 4.47M→1.15M (5445x→1404x)\n   134→- Does NOT help for instances with too-expensive SAT calls (>5s per solve, e.g. twitter with 9.7M hard clauses)\n   135→- Sweet spot: 50-200 unit softs, <1M hard clauses, <500K vars\n   136→\n   137→### Alternating CWLS + WalkSAT-soft\n   138→- **Key discovery**: alternating between CWLS and walksat-soft from an existing solution yields continuous improvement\n   139→- CWLS escapes local optima via dynamic weighting; walksat-soft then explores from the new position\n   140→- Most effective on instances with many soft clauses (>10K)\n   141→- **Game-changer for pa-1**: 4.47M → 688K (5445x → 839x) over ~8 rounds\n   142→- Each round typically reduces cost by 3-8%\n   143→- Eventually converges, but many rounds are worthwhile\n   144→\n   145→### Clause-weighting local search (SATLike-inspired)\n   146→- Dynamically increase weights of unsatisfied soft clauses to escape local optima\n   147→- Periodically smooth weights back to prevent explosion\n   148→- Effective where tabu search gets stuck at single-flip local optima\n   149→- Effective for haplotyping: improved haplotyping-13 from 559K→512K, haplotyping-12 from 963K→668K\n   150→\n   151→### Naive core-guided for correlation-clustering\n   152→- Core-guided (exclude all core literals) works well on correlation-clustering Ionosphere\n   153→  - N280: 32.3M→14.2M (4.50x→1.98x)\n   154→  - N300: 34.3M→16.5M (4.25x→2.04x)\n   155→- Also improved Vowel N700: 144.9M→119.9M (2.00x→1.66x)\n   156→- Works less well on Protein variants (same or worse cost)\n   157→\n   158→## Current bottleneck: single-flip local optima\n   159→Most solved instances are at single-flip local optima — no single variable flip can improve soft cost without breaking hard constraints. Further improvements require:\n   160→1. **Multi-variable moves** (2-opt, 3-opt swaps)\n   161→2. **C/Cython tabu** for faster per-step execution on large instances\n   162→3. **Domain-specific decomposition** (especially for ParametricRBAC, correlation-clustering)\n   163→4. **Longer running times** for tabu search on instances with slow per-step operations\n   164→\n   165→## Approaches that DON'T work\n   166→- **WalkSAT soft on correlation-clustering**: SAT baseline is at hard local optimum, no single flip improves\n   167→- **CaDiCaL baseline for haplotyping**: glucose4 baseline is BETTER for haplotyping (1.2M vs 6.6M)\n   168→- **Tabu search on large occurrence lists**: too slow per step with >1M hard clauses\n   169→- **RC2 on synplicate/timetabling**: times out even with 120s budget — formula too complex\n   170→- **Core-guided with full assumptions on synplicate**: SAT solver hangs — use biased-sat instead\n   171→- **WPM1 on large instances**: returns inf (solver overwhelmed by relaxation constraints)\n   172→- **Biased-sat on twitter (51K softs, 9.7M hards)**: each SAT call too expensive (~5s), no improvement\n   173→- **Greedy SAT with >15K vars per soft call**: each SAT call takes >10s, so greedy loop times out\n   174→\n   175→## Next steps for improvement\n   176→1. **haplotyping (23-29x)**: need clause-weighting LS or tabu from existing best\n   177→2. **polysite-bloat (137x)**: solved but terrible ratio, needs core-guided on unit softs\n   178→3. **relational-inference pa-1 (5445x)**: 2.5M vars, 1.1M softs — needs fundamentally different approach\n   179→4. **timetabling comp09/test4/comp21 (2-4.7x)**: try core-guided (unit softs)\n   180→5. **correlation-clustering (2-4.5x)**: need domain-specific clustering algorithm\n   181→6. **Faster implementations** (Cython/C) for tabu and WalkSAT on large instances\n   182→7. **Solve remaining 9**: 4 MinWeightDomSet too large, 2 lisbon-wedding + 1 MinWeightDomSet have no known ref, 2 relational-inference 18M+ vars\n   183→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38135602-62e8-4094-9f41-0f1fb730f536","uuid":"494338f6-f9f1-4783-8771-09260a70b481","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/agent-sat-1/expert.md","content":"# MaxSAT Expert Knowledge\n\n## Overall results summary\n\n- **220/229 instances solved** (9 remaining)\n- **4 better than competition reference** + 1 with no known reference (pseudoBoolean)\n- **23 optimal** solutions matching reference costs\n- **92 within 1.1x** of reference\n- **183 within 2x**, 36 still >2x\n- **pa-1 reduced from 5445x to ~623x** via biased-sat + alternating CWLS/walksat\n\n## Approach selection guide\n\nThe single most important factor is **number of soft clauses** (nsofts), not total variables or clauses.\n\n### Solver selection: CaDiCaL vs glucose4\n- **CaDiCaL (cd19)** is the default solver for everything. It solved instances in <0.3s where glucose4 was stuck for 10+ minutes.\n- glucose4 ('g4') is only useful for very small instances or as a fallback.\n- The `greedy_sat()` and `sat_init()` functions accept a `solver_name` parameter.\n- **ALWAYS use `solver_name='cd19'`** unless you have a specific reason not to.\n\n### No hard clauses (nhards=0)\n- **Tabu search** with weighted polarity initialization: produces optimal solutions given enough time (250s).\n- Key: polarity init, tabu tenure ~nvars/20.\n- Achieved optimal on all 4 ramsey instances (55-153 vars).\n\n### Few soft clauses (nsofts < 500) with hard clauses\n- **Greedy SAT with selector variables** (CaDiCaL): The most powerful approach.\n  - O(nsofts × SAT_time_per_call), perfect for few-soft instances\n  - Some instances have slow per-call SAT (~seconds), so total time = nsofts × per-call time\n  - Achieved **optimal** or **near-optimal** on: af-synthesis (all 15), preference_planning, synplicate, CSG, lisbon-wedding (most), planning, protein_ins, BTBNSL\n\n### Unit soft clauses with many hard clauses (judgment-aggregation, haplotyping)\n- **Tabu search from existing best** is the most effective approach.\n- judgment-aggregation: all softs unit, all hards 3-literal. ~6K vars, ~1.2M hards.\n  - Starting from fresh SAT init: 20-49x → 1.5-1.8x\n  - Starting from existing best + tabu: further improved to **1.22-1.48x**\n  - Key: load existing solution with `load_solutions()`, seed tabu search from it\n  - Key parameters: restarts=5, perturb_prob=0.05, timeout=240\n\n### Many soft clauses (nsofts > 500) with hard clauses\n- **SAT baseline** gives decent results for most families\n- **Tabu search** can improve but is slow per step for large occurrence lists (>1M hard clauses)\n- **Greedy SAT** with CaDiCaL works for up to ~6000 soft clauses within 300s budget\n\n### Very large instances (>1M vars)\n- CaDiCaL handles many instances that glucose4 cannot (up to ~12M vars in some cases)\n- 9 instances still unsolved — mostly >16M vars or no known reference\n\n## Instance family insights\n\n| Family | Solved | Optimal | Best quality | Notes |\n|--------|--------|---------|-------------|-------|\n| ramsey (4) | 4/4 | 4 | all optimal | Tabu search |\n| synplicate (25) | 25/25 | 5 | 1.0-4.7x | CaDiCaL greedy + multi-init |\n| switchingactivity (9) | 9/9 | 3 | 0.62-3.0x | CaDiCaL greedy, 2 beat reference |\n| af-synthesis (15) | 15/15 | 0 | 1.06-1.23x | CaDiCaL greedy, all solved |\n| protein_ins (7) | 7/7 | 0 | 1.006-1.013x | Near-perfect |\n| BTBNSL (14) | 14/14 | 0 | 1.00-1.5x | 1 beats reference (hailfinder_10000) |\n| decision-tree (15) | 15/15 | 0 | 1.36-3.1x | CaDiCaL greedy + multi-init |\n| judgment-aggregation (13) | 13/13 | 0 | 1.16-1.48x | Tabu from existing best |\n| ParametricRBAC (15) | 15/15 | 0 | 1.0-2.4x | Core-guided + multi-init |\n| lisbon-wedding (13) | 13/13 | 1 | 1.0-2.0x | CaDiCaL greedy+SAT baseline |\n| correlation-clustering (12) | 12/12 | 0 | 1.16-4.5x | Multi-init dramatically improved |\n| abstraction-refinement (11) | 11/11 | 0 | 1.02-137x | polysite-bloat solved via CaDiCaL |\n| timetabling (8) | 8/8 | 2 | 1.0-11.7x | comp07.lp now optimal via core-guided |\n| setcover (6) | 6/6 | 0 | 1.1-1.8x | SAT+tabu |\n| planning (3) | 3/3 | 1 | 1.0-1.29x | |\n| max-realizability (4) | 4/4 | 0 | 1.10-1.29x | Multi-init improved |\n| CSG (2) | 2/2 | 2 | both optimal | |\n| railway-transport (4) | 4/4 | 0 | 1.003-1.64x | CaDiCaL greedy |\n| causal-discovery (5) | 5/5 | 1 | 1.0-2.5x | n7 solved via greedy SAT |\n\n## Key technical insights\n- **CaDiCaL (cd19) >> glucose4** for everything. Always use CaDiCaL.\n- **Greedy SAT with selector variables**: O(nsofts × SAT_time_per_call), the workhorse\n- **Tabu search** with SAT init: transformative for unit soft clauses (judgment-aggregation: 20-49x → 1.5-1.8x)\n- **Core-guided search** is transformative for unit soft clause instances (comp07.lp 1778x→optimal)\n- **SAT solver calls can hang forever** — pysat's `solver.solve()` enters C code and won't return to Python if the problem is too hard. Always use `sat_solve_with_timeout()` from `library/solvers.py` which uses SIGALRM to interrupt hung calls. Without this, core-guided on synplicate hangs indefinitely.\n- **RC2 is unreliable** — times out even on 58-var instances. Don't use.\n- **SAT baseline** is often surprisingly good (abstraction-refinement, BTBNSL, protein_ins, correlation-clustering)\n- Some instances with slow per-call SAT only get partial greedy improvement (lisbon-wedding 9-17, 8-17, 7-19 got baselines only)\n\n## Key packages\n- **python-sat (pysat)**: Solver class with CaDiCaL (cd19) and glucose4 (g4)\n- **numpy**: for custom search implementations\n\n## Notable results\n\n### Better than 2024 MaxSAT competition reference\n- **switchingactivity_74**: cost=10, ref=16 (37.5% better)\n- **switchingactivity_68**: cost=8, ref=9 (11% better)\n- **BTBNSL hailfinder_10000**: cost=49,986,819,152, ref=50,007,681,202 (0.04% better)\n\n### Solved with no known reference (ref=-1 in competition)\n- **pseudoBoolean**: cost=8081 (no competitor found a solution)\n\n## Remaining unsolved (9)\n1. MinimumWeightDominatingSetProblem (4 of 10): delaunay_n24, hugebubbles, inf-road-usa, rgg_n_2_24 — too large (>16M vars)\n2. MinimumWeightDominatingSetProblem socfb-uci-uni: 3.1GB, ref=-1 (no known solution)\n3. lisbon-wedding-1-19 and lisbon-wedding-3-18: ref=-1 (no known solution)\n4. relational-inference pa-2 and pa-3: 18M+ vars\n\n### Multi-init: different SAT solver seeds produce different solutions\n- **Key discovery**: running multiple SAT solvers (cd19, g4, cd15, mc) with random assumptions produces wildly different assignments with different soft costs\n- Extremely effective for breaking out of SAT baseline local optima\n- Example: correlation-clustering Protein1_N270 went from 10.2x to 2.68x just from a different solver seed\n- Example: correlation-clustering Protein1_N250 went from 9.4x to 1.86x\n- Example: decision-tree primary-tumor went from 7.3x to 2.8x\n- Runs 50-500 trials in 15-30s per instance\n- Does NOT help for judgment-aggregation (all SAT baselines are terrible for these)\n\n\n### Core-guided search for unit soft clauses\n- **Key discovery**: many of the worst-ratio instances have unit (single-literal) soft clauses\n- Core-guided approach: use SAT solver assumptions to iteratively find and relax unsatisfiable cores\n- **Game-changer results**:\n  - timetabling comp07.lp: 1778x → **optimal** (cost 3, ref 3)\n  - ParametricRBAC domino: 2.6-3.2x → 1.56-2.44x across all instances\n  - polysite-bloat: unsolved → solved (137x, but solved)\n- Works because unit soft clauses map directly to assumption literals\n- Should be tried on ALL instances with unit soft clauses before other approaches\n\n### Biased-SAT with random assumption subsets\n- **Key discovery**: for instances where full assumption sets hang the solver, random subsets work excellently\n- Creates fresh SAT solver per trial, picks random subset of soft clause literals as assumptions\n- The SAT solver naturally satisfies many soft clauses beyond what's assumed, often finding near-optimal solutions\n- **Game-changer for synplicate family**: where core-guided and RC2 both time out, biased-sat with n=3-40 random assumptions produces rapid improvements\n- Example results:\n  - synplicate dag_run2_12: 959→598 (2.32x→1.45x)\n  - synplicate size10 arity3/f3: 654→507 (3.59x→2.79x)\n  - causal_Water: 15.75M→8.31M (8.35x→4.40x)\n  - relational-inference pa-1: 4.47M→1.15M (5445x→1404x)\n- Does NOT help for instances with too-expensive SAT calls (>5s per solve, e.g. twitter with 9.7M hard clauses)\n- Sweet spot: 50-200 unit softs, <1M hard clauses, <500K vars\n\n### Alternating CWLS + WalkSAT-soft\n- **Key discovery**: alternating between CWLS and walksat-soft from an existing solution yields continuous improvement\n- CWLS escapes local optima via dynamic weighting; walksat-soft then explores from the new position\n- Most effective on instances with many soft clauses (>10K)\n- **Game-changer for pa-1**: 4.47M → 688K (5445x → 839x) over ~8 rounds\n- Each round typically reduces cost by 3-8%\n- Eventually converges, but many rounds are worthwhile\n\n### Clause-weighting local search (SATLike-inspired)\n- Dynamically increase weights of unsatisfied soft clauses to escape local optima\n- Periodically smooth weights back to prevent explosion\n- Effective where tabu search gets stuck at single-flip local optima\n- Effective for haplotyping: improved haplotyping-13 from 559K→512K, haplotyping-12 from 963K→668K\n\n### Naive core-guided for correlation-clustering\n- Core-guided (exclude all core literals) works well on correlation-clustering Ionosphere\n  - N280: 32.3M→14.2M (4.50x→1.98x)\n  - N300: 34.3M→16.5M (4.25x→2.04x)\n- Also improved Vowel N700: 144.9M→119.9M (2.00x→1.66x)\n- Works less well on Protein variants (same or worse cost)\n\n## Current bottleneck: single-flip local optima\nMost solved instances are at single-flip local optima — no single variable flip can improve soft cost without breaking hard constraints. Further improvements require:\n1. **Multi-variable moves** (2-opt, 3-opt swaps)\n2. **C/Cython tabu** for faster per-step execution on large instances\n3. **Domain-specific decomposition** (especially for ParametricRBAC, correlation-clustering)\n4. **Longer running times** for tabu search on instances with slow per-step operations\n\n## Approaches that DON'T work\n- **WalkSAT soft on correlation-clustering**: SAT baseline is at hard local optimum, no single flip improves\n- **CaDiCaL baseline for haplotyping**: glucose4 baseline is BETTER for haplotyping (1.2M vs 6.6M)\n- **Tabu search on large occurrence lists**: too slow per step with >1M hard clauses\n- **RC2 on synplicate/timetabling**: times out even with 120s budget — formula too complex\n- **Core-guided with full assumptions on synplicate**: SAT solver hangs — use biased-sat instead\n- **WPM1 on large instances**: returns inf (solver overwhelmed by relaxation constraints)\n- **Biased-sat on twitter (51K softs, 9.7M hards)**: each SAT call too expensive (~5s), no improvement\n- **Greedy SAT with >15K vars per soft call**: each SAT call takes >10s, so greedy loop times out\n\n## Next steps for improvement\n1. **haplotyping (23-29x)**: need clause-weighting LS or tabu from existing best\n2. **polysite-bloat (137x)**: solved but terrible ratio, needs core-guided on unit softs\n3. **relational-inference pa-1 (5445x)**: 2.5M vars, 1.1M softs — needs fundamentally different approach\n4. **timetabling comp09/test4/comp21 (2-4.7x)**: try core-guided (unit softs)\n5. **correlation-clustering (2-4.5x)**: need domain-specific clustering algorithm\n6. **Faster implementations** (Cython/C) for tabu and WalkSAT on large instances\n7. **Solve remaining 9**: 4 MinWeightDomSet too large, 2 lisbon-wedding + 1 MinWeightDomSet have no known ref, 2 relational-inference 18M+ vars\n","numLines":183,"startLine":1,"totalLines":183}}}
