{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01DJTv63r1dtxfs7p37KeD14","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The ParametricRBAC instances have very few heavy softs (~70) but many medium-weight ones (~34K). The heavy-only approach doesn't help because there are only 70 heavy softs and the medium ones dominate the cost. The heavy-only core-guided doesn't improve because it only optimizes those 70 clauses.\n\nFor ParametricRBAC, I need a different strategy. Let me think...\n\nThe ParametricRBAC instances have:- ~34K unit softs with 4 weight levels- ~2M hard clauses- ~107K vars\n\nWith 34K softs, WPM1 on ALL softs would take a very long time. \n\nCore-guided-budget on all softs was already tried and didn't improve the cost — the problem is that a 300K conflict budget drops too many assumptions. I could try using the current solution as a starting point and refining it with targeted local search, or explore a different problem decomposition. But I think I should shift focus for now and tackle the other instances, particularly twitter which has a 9.65x improvement potential with its 51K softs of weight 1, then circle back to ParametricRBAC later.\n\nFor twitter, I'll focus on applying core-guided search to just the heavier softs (weight 10) rather than all of them.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1843,"cache_read_input_tokens":165767,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1843,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38135602-62e8-4094-9f41-0f1fb730f536","uuid":"5674e866-3cae-4f18-8d9a-2894625428f9"}
