{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01MTTWdqJ8sREpAXt48tuBSd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting. Both core-guided approaches give the same cost (206255 for heavy, 206835 full). Core-guided-solve returns quickly with cost=206255. But for haplotyping-13, WPM1 gave 40670 which is much better.\n\nThe difference must be in the hard clauses — haplotyping-12 might have different hard clause structure that makes the core-guided approach less effective. Let me check what happens with WPM1 — it should process cores more carefully.\n\nLet me trace through why WPM1 returns None so quickly. Looking at the code:\n\n```python\ndef wpm1_solve(nvars, hard_clauses, soft_clauses, timeout=240, solver_name='cd19'):\n\n\n```\n\nAh, I see — WPM1 first validates that all soft clauses are unit clauses, then aggregates weights for duplicate literals. It then iteratively tries to satisfy those literals as assumptions while checking against the hard clauses. This explains why it either finds a good solution quickly or returns None if the hard clauses are too restrictive.\n\nFor haplotyping-12, if the initial solve with all 18400 assumptions is SAT, it should return immediately. If UNSAT, it processes cores and relaxes constraints. The fact that it returned None in 1.2s suggests either the initial solve was SAT but something went wrong, or it exhausted all cores without finding a satisfying assignment.\n\n```\nLet me trace through the cost calculation: 54713 = 581*94 + 99, which would mean 94 heavy softs and 99 light softs violated. But if all heavy softs can be simultaneously satisfied along with the hard clauses, the solver should find that solution with cost just from the light softs. The question is whether sat.solve(assumptions=assumptions) with all 18400 heavy soft literals can actually find a satisfying model.\n```\nFor haplotyping-13, WPM1 found cost 40670 (70 heavy softs violated), confirming not all